<!-- ── FORMULA ── -->
<section class="content-section reveal">
  <h2>The Formula</h2>
  <p>Your take-home pay is what's left after all statutory deductions are removed from your gross salary.</p>
  <div class="formula-box">
    Take-Home Pay = Gross Salary &minus; Income Tax &minus; National Insurance &minus; Pension &minus; Student Loan
  </div>

  <h3>Contractor — inside IR35</h3>
  <p>If you work inside IR35, you're taxed in the same way as an employee. Income tax, National Insurance, and any other deductions are applied to your gross pay just as they would be for a permanent worker.</p>
  <div class="formula-box">
    Take-Home = Contract Income &minus; Income Tax &minus; NI &minus; Pension &minus; Student Loan<br>
    (Same calculation as employed)
  </div>

  <h3>Contractor — outside IR35</h3>
  <p>Outside IR35, you typically pay yourself a small salary up to the Personal Allowance and take the remainder as dividends after corporation tax.</p>
  <div class="formula-box">
    Salary = &pound;12,570 (tax-free Personal Allowance)<br>
    Remaining Profit = Contract Income &minus; Salary &minus; Expenses<br>
    Corporation Tax = Remaining Profit &times; 25%<br>
    Dividends = Remaining Profit &minus; Corporation Tax<br>
    Take-Home = Salary + Dividends (after dividend tax)
  </div>
</section>

